03773nam a22005055i 9780773585102DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735851027 a10.1515/97807735851022doi  a(DE-B1597)657103  a(OCoLC)857638257  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR3316.A4Z48 1988 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a823qOCoLC1 aTroide, Lars E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEarly Journals and Letters of Fanny Burney, Volume 2 /cLars E. Troide. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tShort Titles and Abbreviations -- tTo Samuel Crisp -- tFanny Burney’s First Letter to Thomas Lowndes -- tA Letter of Mrs Elizabeth Allen Burney to Fanny Burney -- tFanny Burney’s Letter to Esther Burney, July 1770 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe years 1774-77 saw Fanny Burney's increasing occupation with Evelina, which she finally completed and presented to the publisher Thomas Lowndes. Like her novel, the journals and letters of this period reveal her artistic powers, as she continues to sketch characters with economy and precision and create convincing narratives out of the events of her life. Among the more memorable figures she meets at her father's London house are the "noble savage" Omai, the first Tahitian brought back to England; the famed explorer James "Abyssinian" Bruce, who returned from Africa with tales of natives who ate raw flesh; and Prince Aleksei Orlov of Russia, who had Czar Peter III murdered in order to permit Peter's wife, Catherine "the Great," to ascend the throne. Other notable figures include Dr Samuel Johnson and the great singer Lucrezia Agujari, admired by Mozart. Also in these pages, the usually diffident Miss Burney takes charge of her destiny by rebuffing her suitor Thomas Barlow, who has wealth, education, good looks, and the vehement approval of most of her family, but whom she finds a total bore. The journals and letters of Fanny Burney are an invaluable source for anyone interested in the social and literary history of late eighteenth- and early nineteenth-century England. Lars Troide has supported the texts with thorough and detailed annotations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358510240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773585102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773585102/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles